’Ů@5f5b5380142702b45f81dd50839d61a57b325a7f1bbec79e9a01ca32572b3d5bÚqTitle: title: to nuon
Path: Examples
Content:
Outputs a NUON string representing the contents of this list, compact by default.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1 2 3] | to nuon
[1, 2, 3]

```
Outputs a NUON array of ints, with pretty indentation.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1 2 3] | to nuon --indent 2
[
  1,
  2,
  3
]

```
Overwrite any set option with --raw.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [1 2 3] | to nuon --indent 2 --raw
[1,2,3]

```
A more complex record with multiple data types.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> {date: 2000-01-01, data: [1 [2 3] 4.56]} | to nuon --indent 2
{
  date: 2000-01-01T00:00:00+00:00,
  data: [
    1,
    [
      2,
      3
    ],
    4.56
  ]
}

```
A more complex record with --raw.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> {date: 2000-01-01, data: [1 [2 3] 4.56]} | to nuon --raw
{date:2000-01-01T00:00:00+00:00,data:[1,[2,3],4.56]}

```
Use raw string syntax for strings with quotes or backslashes.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> 'hello "world"' | to nuon --raw-strings
r#'hello "world"'#

```
Serialize table values as a list of records instead of table syntax.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [[a, b]; [1, 2], [3, 4]] | to nuon --list-of-records
[{a: 1, b: 2}, {a: 3, b: 4}]

```
Serialize table values as list of records with pretty indentation.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
> [[a, b]; [1, 2], [3, 4]] | to nuon --list-of-records --indent 2
[
  {a: 1, b: 2},
  {a: 3, b: 4}
]

```
